The WHO has also published several testing protocols for the disease.
Real-time polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) is the standard testing method.
The test is usually performed on respiratory samples obtained from a nasal swab, but a sample of a nasal swab or sputum may also be used.
The results are usually ready within a period of a few hours to two days.
You can also take blood tests, but they require two blood samples taken at intervals of two weeks, and their results do not directly matter.
