The exact causes of this discrepancy are unknown, but may lie in genetic and behavioral factors.
Gender immunological differences, lower prevalence of smoking among women, concomitant diseases in men (for example, hypertension, manifested in men at a younger age than in women) may be the cause of higher mortality among men.
In Europe, 57% of those infected were men, and 72% of COVID-19 deaths were men.
As of April 2020, the U.S. government does not keep gender statistics on COVID-19.
